Exercise 1

For the provided data set answer the following questions:

  1. What is the data about?
  2. What are different features and their types (discrete, continuous etc, range of values, possible meaning of the features)?
  3. How many rows are in the dataset?

Perform data cleaning and explain the changes that you made.

Solution:

  1. The Adult data set initially consists of \(12\) features that enable us to make different comparisons and analysis. One of the things that the Adult data set represents are the salaries, the capital gain and the capital loss of adult man and women. This data set enables us to compare the income of adults depending on their education, native country, age and the employment. Also we can analyze possible connection between the job satisfaction and the employment type.

  2. The Adult data set contains the following features: X, age, workclass, education, occupation, capital.gain, captital.loss, native.country, salaries, jobsatisfaction, male and female.

  • X: Represents the row number and it is an integer with range between \(1\) and \(32561\).

  • Age: Represents the age of the man and the women in the data set and it is an continous atribute. The range of this feature without cleaning is between \(-57\) and \(320\) which is obviously an incorect range. The correct range of this feature after the cleaning is between \(17\) and \(90\) years.

  • Workclass: Represents the sector in which the adults are working (in case they are employed). Some of the listed occupations are: Private, Federal government, Local government etc.

  • Education: Represents the level of education of the adults.

  • Capital.gain and Capital.loss: Represent the increase/decrease in the value of a capital asset owned by the adults. They are continous integers. The range of the capital gain is between \(0\) and \(99999\) and the range of the capital loss is between \(0\) and \(4356\).

  • Native.country: Represnets the country of residence of the adults. The most frequent country in this data set is the USA.

  • Salaries: Reperesent the adults salary. This feature is a float ranging between \(38.34125\) and \(140000\).

  • Ocupation: Represents the different types of adults jobs, for example: Sales, Transport etc.

  • Job Satisfaction: Represent the job satisfaction of the adults. It is a continous integer between \(0\) and \(15\). \(15\) represent the highest job satisfaction.

  • Male: This feature has two values \(1\) meaning the adult is a male and \(NA\), meaning its not.

  • Female: This feature has two values \(1\) meaning the adult is a female and \(NA\), meaning its not.

The above mentioned ranges and types were found using Open Refine. For demonstration, the range of the data (for example the age feature) and its type can be found in R using:

adult_data <- read.csv("adult-csv.csv")

# Prints the range of the age column:
print(range(adult_data$age, na.rm = TRUE))
## [1] 17 90
# Prints the type of the data:
sapply(adult_data, class)
##             age       workclass       education      occupation 
##       "integer"        "factor"        "factor"        "factor" 
##    capital.gain    capital.loss  native.country        salaries 
##       "integer"       "integer"        "factor"       "numeric" 
## jobsatisfaction          gender 
##       "integer"        "factor"
  1. The initial Adult data set has \(32561\) rows.

Data Cleaning

It is obvious that some of the features are redundant. The X feature can be removed because R already provides us the information about the row number. Also the male and female features can be merged in one column that represents the adults gender.

Using Open Refine we can trim leading and trailing whitespaces that cause some features to be wrongly classified. Then we can examin the content of each individual column using the Text or the Numeric Facet. Using this I:

  • corrected \(-57\) to \(57\) in the age feature;
  • corrected Privat in Private in workclass thus merging them.
  • corrected Unitedstates and UnitedStates in United-States thus merging them.

Additionally the \(?\) sign representing missing data was changed with \(NA\) which is the standard representation of missign data. Also changed with \(NA\) were: * The Very good entry in the jobsatisfaction column (It should be an integer between \(1\) and \(15\)). * The \(320\) age because it is obviously an incorrect value.

Using histogram the distribution for the salaries, the capital.gain, capital.loss, jobsatisfaction and age are plotted.

Using bar plots the distributions for the workclass, education, native.country, gender and occupation are plotted.

The histogram for the age feature is positively skewed arround its mean. We can notice that the mean value is around \(30\).

The skewness for the jobsatisfaction feature is not clearly defined. We can notice that most of the values are concentrated around the elements \(5\) and \(15\).

From the gender distribution we can notice that there are more men then women in this data set. Also, using the workclass distribution we can see that most of the adults work in the private sector. Using the education distribution we can notice that most of the adults are high school grads. Almosut all elements of the occupation distribution are equaly present except the armed forces element. The unproportionaly big number of the element United States in the native.country feature makes the ploting of this feature challenging. The same problem occurs in the capital.gain and capital.loss feature. The range of capital.gain is from \(0\) to 99999 and we have 29849 (almost 92% from the data) in 0 compared to just 159 counts in 99999. The values of capital.loss are also moslty concentrated around 0 (almost 95% from the data).

The high rate of change of the salariess valuea makes the plot difficult to create. Therefore I am splitting the salaries feature in 10 intervals. Then I calculate the median for each of the intervals and I replace the value of the data in the interval with its median. This enables me to plot the data more easily.The median of the new feature is \(34302\), compared to the old value \(33927\).

data_v = na.omit(adult_data)
step = 10000  # interval length
n = ceiling(max(data_v$salaries)/step)  # number of intervals
data_v$salaries_interval = cut(data_v$salaries, step * (0:n))
data_v$salaries_median = ave(data_v$salaries, data_v$salaries_interval, FUN = median)

Also we can group them in \(4\) groups depending on how big the salary is.

data_v$salaries_group = ifelse(test = data_v[, "salaries"] >= 0 & data_v[, "salaries"] <= 
    30000, yes = "Salary 0 - 30000", no = ifelse(test = data_v[, "salaries"] > 
    30000 & data_v[, "salaries"] <= 60000, yes = "Salary 30001 - 60000", no = ifelse(test = data_v[, 
    "salaries"] > 60000 & data_v[, "salaries"] <= 90000, yes = "Salary 60001 - 90000", 
    no = "Salary 90001 - 140 000")))

We can notice that we have only \(4\) salaries in the range between \(90001\) and \(140000\).

Exercise 3

Identify potential outliers in the (numerical features) dataset by applying inter-quartile ranges (IQR) (range between the \(25%\) and \(75%\) quartiles) - are there values that are over \(k*IQR\) larger the upper quartile or \(k*IQR\) below lower quartile. Use \(k=1.5\).

Explain if you should remove outliers. If so, then which ones. The outliers may show up from mistakes (incorrect data input, measurement error) or actually correct but rare values. You do not need to decide for each observation separately but explain your chosen outlier exclusion criteria in general terms. Decide and remove identified outliers and recalculate statistics from ex 2 for the changed features (including the plot). Any observations?

Solution:

Outlier is an observation point that is distant from other observations. Using R we can find the data points that are distinctly separate from the rest of the data.

max_age <- quantile(adult_data[, 1], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE) + (IQR(adult_data[, 
    1], na.rm = TRUE) * 1.5)
min_age <- quantile(adult_data[, 1], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE) - (IQR(adult_data[, 
    1], na.rm = TRUE) * 1.5)
out_age <- which(adult_data[, 1] < min_age | adult_data[, 1] > max_age)

print(paste(length(out_age), sep = " "))
## [1] "143"
print(paste(max_age, min_age))
## [1] "78 -2"
out_age <- sort(out_age)

# adult_data <- adult_data[-out_age,] We can remove the outliers using this.

For the Age Feature we can see that we have \(143\) outliers and all of them lie above the upper fence. However these outliers should not be removed because the reason for this values is not a measurment error (the age between \(78\) and \(90\) is a possible value).

We can visualize the outliers using box plot.

Similarly we calculate the outliers for capital.gain and capital.loss. For capital.gain we have \(2712\) outliers and for capital.loss we have \(1519\) outliers. In the both cases everything that is not zero is concidered to be an outlier. Removing this outliers depends of the final analysis we want to perform with out data set. The values above \(0\) are possible values. If we remove the outliers we will get identical mean and median that will have a value of \(0\).

For the salaries feature we have \(195\) outliers and all of them lie above the upper fence (above \(79983.5\)). The values above \(79983.5\) are possible because adults can have higher salary than this. As a result this outliers should not be removed. If we remove them we will get lower value for the mean which will be closer to the median.

The job satisfaction feature does not have any outliers.

The total number of outliers in the data set is \(4569\).

Exercise 4

There are some missing values in features age and native.country. Investigate, which cases of missing data do we have in each of our features (systematically or randomly missing). Make a decision if you can or should impute missing data in some of those features and explain your decision. If you decided to impute, do that (you dont have to use anything too complicated) and compare relevant statistics and plots from ex 2 with the values on initial dataset. If you decide not to impute, explain (and convince us) on the reason why.

Solution:

Missing data, or missing values, occur when no data value is stored for the variable in an observation. This is a common occurrence that can have a significant effect on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data. The missing data in native.country occurs completely at random. In other words there is no clear pattern that connects the missing data in native.country with the other features and we can not find any convincing evidence that any connection exists.Although R eliminate cases with missing data, the \(NA\) cases in this feature consist just \(1.79%\) of the data set which means we have enough data to perform the analysis.

On the other hand in the age feature we can notice that all of the missing values occur when the education is Doctorate.This gives us an evidence that maybe the respondents refused to answer the question because of privacy or any other issues. A simple approach to deal with this missing data is to change the missing values with the median of the age of the adults whouse education is Doctorate. However, I do not expect significant changes in the distibution because the \(NA\) cases in this feature consist just \(0.29%\) of the data.

The median of the doctors age is \(47\).

Changing the \(NA\) values with \(47\) in the age features result with the following values: mean: \(38.5858\) median: \(37\) standard deviation: \(13.63024\)

The median remains the same and the mean and the standard deviation have insignificant changes compared to the old values.

From the plots we can also notice that we did not introduce significant change in the distribtion.
